ğŸ“– Lesson Content
â€¢ Why Archive? ğŸ¯ â€” Memory (prevents revisionism), Leverage (invites oversight), Safety (antiâ€‘spoliation), and Teaching (others can replicate).
â€¢ What to Preserve ğŸ“¦ â€” Filings, orders, docket prints, clerk emails/returns, carrier receipts, portal confirmations, call logs, transcripts/transcript orders, declarations, processâ€‘server affidavits, timeâ€‘stamped screenshots, and press correspondence.
â€¢ Structure & Naming ğŸ§­ â€” YYYYâ€‘MMâ€‘DD prefix + short slug + exhibit tag (e.g., 2025â€‘06â€‘12_FedEx_ExA.pdf). Keep a master **Exhibit Index** with: ID, Date, Event, Source, Docket #/ECF, Exhibit label, Hash (SHAâ€‘256), Privacy level (Public/Restricted), Notes.
â€¢ Integrity & Versioning ğŸ” â€” Use PDF/A and OCR, add bookmarks, Batesâ€‘stamp exhibits, maintain a **hash manifest** (SHAâ€‘256), and use version tags (v1.0.0). Keep an immutable 'originals' folder and a 'publicâ€‘redacted' folder.
â€¢ Legal Interfaces âš–ï¸ â€” Build for: FRE 201 (judicial notice of public records), FRE 1006 (summaries of voluminous records), Rule 37(e) (spoliation). Mind protective orders; when needed, file motions to seal/redact; maintain a redaction log.
